API Gateway
----------
An API Gateway is a server that acts as a single entry point for clients to access multiple backend services.

1️⃣ Request Routing
Sends requests to the correct microservice.
2️⃣ Authentication & Authorization
Verifies user identity (e.g., JWT tokens, OAuth).
3️⃣ Rate Limiting
Prevents abuse by limiting how many requests a client can make.
4️⃣ Load Balancing
Distributes traffic across multiple instances of a service.
5️⃣ Caching
Stores responses temporarily to reduce backend load.
6️⃣ Logging & Monitoring
Tracks request data for analytics and debugging

Popular API Gateway Tools
🔹 Amazon API Gateway - Managed service from AWS for building and managing APIs.
🔹 Kong - Open-source and enterprise API gateway.
🔹 NGINX - Often used as a lightweight API gateway or reverse proxy.
🔹 Apigee - Google’s API management platform.


Gateway API
-----------
A Gateway API is just an API exposed through an API Gateway / set of endpoints clients use through that gateway

The Kubernetes Gateway API is a modern way to manage how traffic enters and moves inside a Kubernetes cluster. It replaces and improves the older Ingress system.

Feature	        Gateway API	    Ingress
Design	        Modular	        Monolithic
Protocols	    HTTP, TCP, gRPC	Mostly HTTP
Role separation	Yes	            No
Flexibility	    High	        Limited

Kubernetes Gateway API is a next-generation traffic routing system that gives you fine-grained, scalable, and role-based control over how requests reach your applications.

HTTPRoute
---------
HTTPRoute is a resource that defines how HTTP/HTTPS requests are routed to backend services inside your Kubernetes cluster.